# The Scarlet Rot · the bloom that devours from within

The Scarlet Rot is the power of an Outer God of decay and rebirth — a crimson corruption that blooms through flesh and land alike, flowering into grotesque beauty. It does not merely destroy; it transforms, turning body and soil into a garden of its own crimson order. Wherever it takes hold, the boundary between ruin and blossom dissolves.

Its most famous vessel is Malenia, who carries the rot sealed within her from birth. It costs her limb after limb, and at the last she blooms as its goddess in Elphael — the corruption she contained her whole life finally flowering through her. Beneath the earth lies the lake of rot, and the kindred of rot, too, worship the rot's power.

Crucially, the lore does not frame the rot as evil so much as a rival order: decay as another kind of cycle, set against the cycles the world already knows. It is an order of composting and re-flowering — ruin running on its own crimson schedule.

Its emergence is natural because the rot is decay itself — embodied, organic, working through flesh and land the way rot works through any living thing. Whatever god stands behind it, the power arrives in the world as bloom, blight, and soil: the land's own processes turned crimson.
